TETANUS, CATTLE, SHEEP - BRAZIL (RIO GRANDE DO SUL)
**************************************************
A ProMED-mail post
<promed@promedmail.org>
ProMED-mail, a program of the
International Society for Infectious Diseases
<http://www.isid.org>
[1]
Date: 3 Jul 2001
From: ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>
Source: Agencia EFE, 3 July 2001 [edited]

RIO DE JANEIRO: Brazilian agricultural authorities are investigating a
tetanus outbreak that has killed more than 300 head of cattle over the last
month in the state of Rio Grande do Sul. "The investigation is being
conducted by the Ministry of Agriculture, which has not yet verified
whether or not the disease was transmitted by a vermicide," said a
spokesperson for the Rio Grande do Sul Agriculture Secretariat.
Preliminary exams reportedly indicate the outbreak was caused by a
vermicide used to kill intestinal worms. Agriculture officials said they
expect to announce an answer sometime this week.
On 12 Jun 2001, veterinarians from 3 separate universities confirmed the
presence of tetanus in the first reported case at the Nossa Senhora do
Rosario ranch in Brazil's southernmost state.
Federal agricultural authorities stepped in after confirming cattle in at
least 3 municipalities have died of tetanus.
­­
